**Code Explanation:**

The script loads the training logs from Steps 2 and 3 and groups the data by condition (vanilla, condition_A, condition_B). It interpolates the episode rewards to a common step grid (0 to 30,000 steps) to compute the mean and standard deviation of the learning curves across the 5 seeds. It calculates the sample efficiency by finding the first step where the interpolated reward reaches 90% of the global maximum average reward. If a condition never reaches this threshold, its sample efficiency is capped at the maximum number of steps (30,000). Final upright stability is extracted from the last evaluation metric. Statistical tests (independent t-tests) are performed to compare Condition A and Condition B on final performance, sample efficiency, and final stability. A safe t-test wrapper is used to handle cases with zero variance. A 2D grid of states is generated with theta in [-pi, pi] and dot(theta) in [-8, 8]. The median-performing seed for Condition A and Condition B is identified based on the final cumulative reward, and the corresponding trained models are loaded. The analytic Lyapunov function Phi(s), the learned Q-values for Condition A and Condition B, and the learned residual for Condition B are computed across the grid using the deterministic policy action (the mean of the actor distribution). Finally, all computed metrics and grid data are saved to disk as .pkl and .npz files, respectively, and the key statistics are printed to the console.

**Modifications:**

The code was structured to ensure all logic is contained within the main block, relative imports are used correctly, and file paths are directed to the data/ directory. The script was verified to avoid any command-line arguments and to use only standard libraries or pre-approved dependencies.

